## 🖼️ Replacing Placeholder Illustrations

All event cards, blog headers, and the founder portrait use hand-drawn SVG illustrations as placeholders. To swap in real photos:

1. Add your `.jpg` or `.webp` images to the `/images/` folder
2. Find the `<div class="event-img">` (or `.blog-img`, `.founder-img`) in the relevant HTML file
3. Replace the `<svg>` block with:

```html
<img src="images/your-photo.jpg" alt="Description of photo"
     style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;" />
```

---

## 🔗 Updating Event Links

Each event card has a booking button pointing to Eventbrite:

```html
<a class="btn btn-primary" href="https://www.eventbrite.com" target="_blank">
  Book on Eventbrite →
</a>
```

Replace `https://www.eventbrite.com` with the real Eventbrite event URL.

---

## 📅 Updating the Calendar

Events are defined in `js/main.js` in the `CAL_EVENTS` object:

```js
var CAL_EVENTS = {
  '2026-4-19':  'Skagit Valley Tulip Festival',
  '2026-5-3':   'Tea & Trails: Snohomish',
  // Add more events here: 'YYYY-M-D': 'Event Name'
};
```

Format: `'YEAR-MONTH-DAY'` (no leading zeros on month or day).

---

## 📬 Connecting the Contact Form

The contact form currently shows a visual confirmation on submit. To connect it to a real backend:

**Option A — Formspree (free, easy):**
1. Sign up at [formspree.io](https://formspree.io)
2. Create a new form and get your endpoint URL
3. In `contact.html`, update the submit handler in `js/main.js` to POST to your Formspree endpoint

**Option B — Mailchimp / ConvertKit:**
Replace the newsletter form action with your Mailchimp embed code.

---

## 📱 Social Media Links

Update the `href="#"` placeholders in every footer and the contact page:

```html
<a class="social-link" href="https://instagram.com/shegoesoutside" title="Instagram">📸</a>
<a class="social-link" href="https://facebook.com/shegoesoutside" title="Facebook">👍</a>
<!-- etc. -->
```

---

## 🚀 Deploying

This is a **pure static site** — no build step needed.

**GitHub Pages (free):**
1. Push this folder to a GitHub repo
2. Go to Settings → Pages → Source: `main` branch, `/ (root)`
3. Your site will be live at `https://yourusername.github.io/she-goes-outside`

**Netlify (recommended for custom domain):**
1. Drag and drop the folder at [netlify.com/drop](https://app.netlify.com/drop)
2. Connect a custom domain like `shegoesoutside.com`

